<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870427-0021 </DOCNO><HL> What's News --Business and Finance</HL><DD> 04/27/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   CONSUMER PRICES ROSE 0.4% in March, suggesting the weak dollar is starting to push up prices for a broad range of items. There were big increases in the cost of housing, apparel and energy. Separately, personal income edged up 0.2% last month. Machine tool orders declined 23% as General Motors, a major purchaser, slashed its spending.    ---   Tougher trade laws appear likely to be approved by Congress soon. The protectionist movement has been bolstered partly by growing corporate support. Meanwhile, Nakasone will try to ease U.S.-Japan trade tensions during talks with Reagan this week.    ---   Interest rates may rise again soon due to the weak dollar and a wave of federal borrowing. Bond and stock prices tumbled Friday as the dollar's slide continued, raising doubts about the effectiveness of intervention.    Treasury Secretary Baker rejected calls that the U.S. issue yen-denominated bonds to bolster the dollar.    ---   Goldman Sachs andamp; Co. and Salomon Brothers have sharply restricted employees' personal speculation in stocks and options. The two big investment banking concerns cited Wall Street's insider-trading scandal.    ---   Takeover legislation will be introduced by two House Democrats today. The bill would put target firms on a more equal footing with corporate raiders and bring unconventional takeovers under federal regulation.    ---   Burlington Industries received a takeover bid of $60 a share, or $1.51 billion, from investor Asher Edelman and Dominion Textile of Montreal. They didn't rule out a hostile offer for the big U.S. textile company.    ---   Florida's new services tax is already creating a national backlash. Attorneys, advertising groups and others in and outside the state are scrambling to have the law nullified, though their chances are uncertain.    ---   The Farm Credit System is likely to have a $1.4 billion loss this year and a total deficit of $3.3 billion over the next three years, the farm lender's regulatory agency said.    ---   The Farm Credit System is likely to have a $1.4 billion loss this year and a total deficit of $3.3 billion over the next three years, the farm lender's regulatory agency said.    ---   United Air's pilots union may seek a partner to help it acquire the carrier. The union's $4.5 billion bid was rejected by UAL Friday. Separately, major airlines are posting better-than-expected quarterly results.    ---   Texaco exhausted its final appeal on the facts surrounding its $10.3 billion legal battle with Pennzoil. Texaco's prospects now depend on economic issues and legal theory.    ---   Exxon's earnings fell 37% in the first quarter, reflecting the slump in the energy industry. Phillips Petroleum reported a $32 million loss, while Shell Oil's profit tumbled 60%.    ---   Chrysler is cutting merit pay and other benefits for 1,800 executives as part of a belt-tightening move.    ---   Mobil is moving its world-wide headquarters from New York to Fairfax, Va., a Washington suburb.    ---   Two top Reagan officials asked Congress to raise the U.S. debt ceiling by mid-May, warning that delay could bring an unprecedented default.    ---   Procter andamp; Gamble's profit rose 13% in its latest quarter, generally matching analysts' estimates.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 177,960,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2335.37, off 45.60; transportation 913.47, off 15.80; utilities 199.33, off 3.69.    Bonds: Shearson Lehman Treasury index 1277.23, off 21.27.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 126.60, up 1.77; spot index 126.61, up 2.48.    Dollar: 139.38 yen, off 1.27; 1.7845 marks, off 0.0218. </TEXT></DOC>